Seius Strabo: the father of Seja- nus, who was afterwards associated with him in this office.

The praetorian praefect, praefec- tus praetorio, at first merely com· mander of the emperor’s body-guard, was afterwards the most powerful

’ officer in the state. The praetorian

cohorts were nine in number, each of a thousand men commanded by a tribune, the whole body being regularly commanded by two prae- fects (at this time only one). Three of these cohorts were stationed in the city, the rest in other parts of Italy ; but Sejanus concentrated the whole body in a fortified camp just outside the city walls. This prae- torian camp served as a fortress to keep the city in subjection.
